            transition: background-color 0.2s ease;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        .results {
            background-color: #e9f5ff;
            border: 1px solid #b3d9ff;
            padding: 15px;
            border-radius: 4px;
            margin-top: 20px;
            max-height: 300px;
            overflow-y: auto;
        }
        .results h3 {
            margin-top: 0;
            color: #0056b3;
        }
        .product-list {
            list-style: none;
            padding: 0;
        }
        .product-item {
            background-color: #f9fcff;
            border: 1px solid #d0e9ff;
            padding: 10px;
            margin-bottom: 8px;
            border-radius: 4px;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
            align-items: center;
        }
        .product-item strong {
            color: #333;
        }
        .product-item span {
            color: #666;
            font-size: 0.9em;
        }
        .query-display {
            background-color: #f8f8f8;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            padding: 10px;
            border-radius: 4px;
            font-family: 'Courier New', Courier, monospace;
            white-space: pre-wrap;
            word-break: break-all;
            margin-top: 10px;
            color: #555;
        }
        .explanation {
            background-color: #e6f7ff;
            border-left: 5px solid #007bff;
            padding: 15px;
            margin-top: 25px;
            border-radius: 4px;
        }
        .explanation h3 {
            color: #007bff;
            margin-top: 0;
        }
        .warning {
            color: #dc3545;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
        .success {
            color: #28a745;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>SQL Injection Demonstration</h1>
        <p>
            This page demonstrates the concept of SQL Injection using an in-memory JavaScript "database" (an array of objects).
            You can compare a <strong>vulnerable</strong> search interface (using string concatenation) with a <strong>safe</strong> one (using parameterized filtering).
        </p>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Our Mock Product Database</h2>
            <p>This is the data we'll be searching through:</p>
            <div class="query-display">
                <pre id="databaseContent"></pre>
            </div>
            <button onclick="showAllProducts()">Show All Products (Raw)</button>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Vulnerable Search (String Concatenation)</h2>
            <p class="warning">
                This search interface is <strong>vulnerable</strong> to SQL Injection. It directly embeds user input into the "query string".
            </p>
            <label for="vulnerableSearchTerm">Search for Products (e.g., 'Laptop', 'Mouse'):</label>
            <input type="text" id="vulnerableSearchTerm" placeholder="Enter search term">
            <button onclick="searchVulnerable()">Search (Vulnerable)</button>

            <div class="results">
                <h3>Simulated Query (Vulnerable):</h3>
                <div id="vulnerableQuery" class="query-display"></div>
                <h3>Results:</h3>
                <ul id="vulnerableResults" class="product-list">
                    <li>No results yet.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Safe Search (Parameterized Filtering)</h2>
            <p class="success">
                This search interface is <strong>safe</strong> against SQL Injection. It uses parameterized filtering,
                treating user input purely as data, not as executable code.
            </p>
            <label for="safeSearchTerm">Search for Products (e.g., 'Keyboard', 'Monitor'):</label>
            <input type="text" id="safeSearchTerm" placeholder="Enter search term">
            <button onclick="searchSafe()">Search (Safe)</button>

            <div class="results">
                <h3>Simulated Query (Safe):</h3>
                <div id="safeQuery" class="query-display"></div>
                <h3>Results:</h3>
                <ul id="safeResults" class="product-list">
                    <li>No results yet.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="explanation">
            <h2>Understanding the Difference: Why Parameterized Queries Work</h2>
            <p>
                In a real database system, SQL Injection occurs when an attacker manipulates a SQL query by injecting
                malicious code into user input fields. The database then executes this manipulated query, often
                leading to unauthorized data access, modification, or even deletion.
            </p>
            <p><strong>1. Vulnerable Approach (String Concatenation):</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>The server constructs the SQL query by literally stitching together parts of the query string with user input.</li>
                <li>If the user inputs something like `' OR 1=1 --`, the server's generated query might look like:
                    <code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE '%user_input%' OR 1=1 --%';</code>
                </li>
                <li>The <code>'</code> closes the original string, <code>OR 1=1</code> creates a condition that is always true,
                    and <code>--</code> comments out the rest of the original query, making the entire condition true
                    and returning all records.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>2. Safe Approach (Parameterized Queries / Prepared Statements):</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>The server first defines the structure of the SQL query with placeholders for user input (e.g., <code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE ?</code>).</li>
                <li>Then, it sends the user's input separately to the database as a "parameter".</li>
                <li>The database treats this parameter purely as data, regardless of what it contains. It doesn't interpret
                    any special characters (like <code>'</code>, <code>OR</code>, <code>--</code>) within the parameter as executable SQL.</li>
                <li>So, if the user inputs `' OR 1=1 --`, the database will search for a product name literally matching
                    <code>'% ' OR 1=1 -- %'</code>, which is highly unlikely to exist, preventing the injection.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                In this JavaScript demo, we simulate this behavior. The "vulnerable" search interprets special characters
                in your input as part of the filtering logic, while the "safe" search treats your input as a literal string
                to match against product names.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Try these inputs in the vulnerable search:</strong></p>
            <ul>
