            <h2>Understanding SQL Injection</h2>

            <p>SQL Injection is a web security vulnerability that allows an attacker to interfere with the queries that an application makes to its database. It usually allows an attacker to view data that they are not normally able to retrieve, and in some cases, modify or delete data, or even issue administrative commands to the database.</p>

            <h3>How it Works (Vulnerable Mode):</h3>
            <p>In the <strong>Vulnerable Mode</strong>, the application directly concatenates user input into the "SQL query" string. Imagine our JavaScript filtering function as a simplified SQL engine. When you input something like <code>' OR '1'='1</code>, the "query" becomes:</p>
            <p><code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE '%user_input%'</code></p>
            <p>If <code>user_input</code> is <code>' OR '1'='1</code>, the resulting string for the filter might look like:</p>
            <p><code>product.name.includes('') OR '1'=='1'</code></p>
            <p>The <code>'</code> closes the initial string, <code>OR '1'='1'</code> is added, and <code>--</code> (or a trailing <code>'</code>) can comment out or close the rest of the original query. Since <code>'1'='1'</code> is always true, the condition becomes true for all products, effectively returning everything.</p>
            <p>In this JavaScript demo, we simulate this by constructing a dynamic JavaScript <code>eval()</code> expression or a highly flexible filter function that interprets the input as part of the logic.</p>
            <p class="warning"><strong>Danger:</strong> This allows attackers to manipulate the database query, bypass authentication, extract sensitive data, or even compromise the entire system.</p>

            <h3>How Parameterized Queries Prevent It (Safe Mode):</h3>
            <p>In the <strong>Safe Mode</strong>, we use <em>parameterized queries</em> (also known as prepared statements). Instead of concatenating user input directly into the query string, placeholders are used in the query, and the user input is passed as separate parameters.</p>
            <p>The "SQL query" structure remains fixed:</p>
            <p><code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE ?</code></p>
            <p>When the user inputs <code>' OR '1'='1</code>, the database treats the *entire* input string (<code>' OR '1'='1</code>) as a single literal value for the <code>?</code> placeholder. It does not interpret any part of it as executable code or a change to the query's structure.</p>
            <p>So, the database effectively searches for a product name that literally contains the string <code>' OR '1'='1</code>. Since no product is likely to have such a name, the malicious input fails to alter the query's intent.</p>
            <p>In our JavaScript demo, this means the user input is always treated as a plain string for comparison, not as a piece of code to be executed or interpreted as part of the filter logic.</p>
            <p><strong>Key Principle:</strong> Parameterized queries separate the query's structure from its data, ensuring that user input can never be confused with executable code.</p>
