        <section class="explanation">
            <h2>Why Parameterized Queries Work</h2>
            <p>
                The core problem with SQL Injection (and similar injection attacks in other contexts) is that the application treats user-supplied <strong>data</strong> as part of the executable <strong>code</strong> (the query).
            </p>
            <h3>1. The Vulnerable Approach (String Concatenation):</h3>
            <p>
                When you build a query by directly concatenating user input into a SQL string, like:
                <code>"SELECT * FROM products WHERE name = '" + userInput + "'"</code>
                the database engine sees one single string. If <code>userInput</code> is <code>' OR 1=1 --</code>, the resulting query becomes:
                <code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE name = '' OR 1=1 --'</code>.
                The <code>--</code> turns the rest of the original query into a comment, and <code>OR 1=1</code> is always true, effectively bypassing the original filter and returning all records.
            </p>
            <p>
                The database has no way to distinguish between the intended data and the injected code. It just executes the final, combined string.
            </p>

            <h3>2. The Safe Approach (Parameterized Queries):</h3>
            <p>
                With parameterized queries (or prepared statements), you define the structure of the query first, marking placeholders for where data will go:
                <code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE name = ?</code> (or <code>:name</code>, <code>@name</code> depending on the database system).
            </p>
            <p>
                Then, you provide the user input separately as a parameter for that placeholder. The database engine processes these two parts distinctly:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>It first parses and compiles the query structure (<code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE name = ?</code>). It understands that <code>?</code> is a placeholder for a value.</li>
                <li>Then, it takes the user input (e.g., <code>' OR 1=1 --</code>) and treats it *only* as a literal string value to be inserted into that placeholder. It automatically escapes any special characters within the user input.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                So, if <code>userInput</code> is <code>' OR 1=1 --</code>, the database will treat the *entire string* <code>' OR 1=1 --</code> as the value for the <code>name</code> column. It will look for a product whose name is literally <code>' OR 1=1 --</code>, which is highly unlikely to exist, and thus no injection occurs.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>The key takeaway:</strong> Parameterized queries ensure that user input is always treated as <strong>data</strong>, never as executable <strong>code</strong>. This separation of concerns is fundamental to preventing injection attacks.
            </p>
        </section>
    </div>

    <script>
        // In-memory product database
        const products = [
