        <div class="explanation">
            <h3>Why Parameterized Queries Work (and String Concatenation Fails)</h3>
            <p>Imagine your database query is like a structured command given to a server. This command has two distinct parts:</p>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>The Instruction (SQL Code):</strong> What operation to perform (e.g., SELECT, UPDATE, DELETE).</li>
                <li><strong>The Data (User Input):</strong> The actual values to use in the instruction (e.g., the product name to search for).</li>
            </ol>

            <h4>Vulnerable (String Concatenation):</h4>
            <p>When you use string concatenation, the server sees your user input as <span class="warning">part of the instruction itself</span>. It blindly pastes whatever you type directly into the SQL command. If your input contains SQL keywords (like <code>OR</code>, <code>DROP TABLE</code>, <code>--</code>), the database interprets them as changes to the original command's logic or structure.</p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
            <p>Original SQL template: <code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE '%<span style="color:red;">USER_INPUT</span>%'</code></p>
            <p>If <code>USER_INPUT</code> is <code>'; DROP TABLE products; --</code>, the combined string becomes:</p>
            <pre><code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE '%<span style="color:blue;">'</span><span style="color:red;">; DROP TABLE products; --</span>%'</code></pre>
            <p>The database sees this as:
            <ol>
                <li>Select products where name is like an empty string (the first <code>'</code> closes the previous string).</li>
                <li>Then, <span class="warning">DROP THE PRODUCTS TABLE</span>.</li>
                <li>Ignore everything after <code>--</code> (the comment).</li>
            </ol>
            <p>This allows an attacker to inject entirely new SQL commands, altering the intended logic or executing malicious operations.</p>

            <h4>Safe (Parameterized Filtering):</h4>
            <p>With parameterized queries (or prepared statements), you define the structure of your SQL command first, with placeholders for where user data will go. The database then understands that anything provided for these placeholders is <span class="strong">pure data</span>, never executable code.</p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
            <p>SQL template: <code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE ?</code> (the <code>?</code> is a placeholder)</p>
            <p>Data parameter: <code>'%<span style="color:red;">'; DROP TABLE products; --</span>%'</code></p>
            <p>The database treats the entire input <code>'; DROP TABLE products; --</code> as just a string value to compare against product names. It will literally search for a product name that contains the characters <code>'; DROP TABLE products; --</code>. It will <span class="strong">never</span> execute <code>DROP TABLE</code> because that part of the string is seen as data, not an instruction.</p>
            <p>This strict separation of code and data is the fundamental reason why parameterized queries prevent SQL injection.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

